text: As Vice Chairman of the Senate Intelligence Committee, I will continue pressing the nation‚Äôs intelligence leaders and the social media companies to be far more aggressive and proactive in responding to this ongoing threat.

This indictment also tells us we all have more work to do. While social media allows Americans to communicate and share ideas in ways unimaginable just a decade ago, we each bear some responsibility for exercising good judgment and a healthy amount of skepticism online.

The indictment confirms what we heard this week from the nation‚Äôs top intelligence officials: Russia is still using social media to attack our democratic institutions and sow division amongst Americans.

This indictment vindicates the Senate Intelligence Committee's bipartisan investigation into Russia's interference in the 2016 election, particularly its focus on uncovering and exposing the role that social media disinformation played in that effort.

This indictment shows that the "Internet Research Agency," a Russian troll farm, was a key component of Russia's interference in the 2016 elections, and that it continues to spew divisive and false content aimed at undermining the United States.
With this indictment, the Special Counsel and his team have taken an important step to hold Russia accountable for its attack on America's democracy.

text: Elected leaders, particularly those entrusted with our nation‚Äôs secrets, must live up to the trust placed in them by their colleagues and the American people. Starting right now. History is watching.

Even Trump-appointed officials at the FBI have voiced ‚Äúgrave concerns‚Äù about its accuracy, and his appointees at the DOJ have warned that releasing the memo would be ‚Äúextraordinarily reckless.‚Äù

FISA warrants and other classified intelligence materials aren‚Äôt toys for members of Congress to use in partisan games. They‚Äôre important tools that the dedicated men and women of the Intelligence community use to keep us safe and literally save American lives.

There are processes in our government that allow for declassification in a reasonable, rational way that protects the sources and methods of our intelligence community. This political charade with the #NunesMemo isn‚Äôt it.

As a member of Congress, getting appointed to an Intelligence Committee is a very sobering proposition. You hear things that you have to keep secret, that you can‚Äôt share with anyone, because you know if you do reveal classified information, people can die.
This is not the way the United States government operates, and it is not the way members of the Intelligence Committees are supposed to act.

I‚Äôve seen the underlying Intelligence documents behind the #NunesMemo, and it is a distortion of the facts. Anyone can selectively pick documents out of a huge storyline and cook up a case. That doesn‚Äôt make it true.

text: I hope my concerns are unfounded, but there are troubling signs.  It is critical that we as elected officials, and as citizens, speak up against these threats now‚Ä¶before it is too late.

Congress must make clear to the President that firing the Special Counsel, or interfering with his investigation by issuing pardons of essential witnesses, is unacceptable, and would have immediate and significant consequences.
In the United States of America, no one is above the law. Not even the President.
Firing Mr. Mueller or any of the top brass involved in this investigation would call into question this Administration‚Äôs commitment to the truth and the rule of law.

While the President has said he is not considering removing Special Counsel Mueller, the President‚Äôs track record on this front is a source of concern.  I‚Äôm certain many of my colleagues believed that he wouldn‚Äôt possibly fire Mr. Comey, either.
These statements are reckless. They are inappropriate. And they are extremely worrying.

In recent weeks, a growing chorus of voices in Congress, the media, and the White House have begun pushing a coordinated narrative undermining the credibility of the Special Counsel‚Äôs investigation and the FBI itself.
Any of these actions would be a gross abuse of power and a flagrant violation of Executive branch responsibilities and authorities. These are red lines, and we simply cannot allow them to be crossed.

That means:
 
- Firing Robert Mueller or top FBI or DOJ brass overseeing the investigation.

- Pardoning key witnesses in an effort to shield them from accountability

- Any other attempt to shut down the investigation
It's time to draw the line: any attempt by President Trump to interfere with Special Counsel Robert Mueller's investigation would provoke a constitutional crisis.

Currently eligibility is calculated based on the presence of ANY VA facility within 40 miles, whether it has the required service or not.
S.1463 will change the 40-mile calculation to be based on the nearest VA facility that provides the service being sought by the veteran.
The Senate just unanimously voted to make an important fix to the way the 40-mile rule in the Veterans Choice Program is calculated.
